t all necessary permissions and conditions are properly accounted for to avoid any pitfalls in the process.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering git commit adjustments**\\n\\nI’m thinking that a commit should ideally represent just the changes relative to HEAD. If I'm replacing three entries with one, that might be okay. However, my working tree has other modifications, which makes `git status` show changes. I could stage just the hunk I want using a patch applied with `git apply --cached`. Since the whole file is modified, `git add -p` could also work interactively, but it may be tricky with a noninteractive tool. It might be best to keep updating the working tree file since external workflows rely on it too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Staging changes effectively**\\n\\nI think I should use the edit tool on the working tree file first. After that, I can run `git diff` to create a patch or use `git add -p` to stage just the specific hunk. Staging the entire file with `git add path` would include unrelated unstaged changes, which might not be ideal unless those changes are from the user. It seems best to use `git apply --cached` with a minimal patch after editing, and I'll do the same for the test file if it’s modified since there aren’t other changes to worry about.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Modifying test file content**\\n\\nI'm working on modifying the test file. It's good that there are no other unstaged changes in that file. I think I might create a new commit on top of the previous commit after editing it. \\n\\nI want to keep imports concise, so I'm crafting the `RecordsHelpersDynamicAccessTest` class with relevant tests. For the assertions, I need to decide on how to check map entries effectively without losing order. Using `assertThat` to check the key set or entries is the direction I’m thinking!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining SampleRecord behavior**\\n\\nI'm looking at the `SampleRecord` definition, which has an auxiliary constructor allowing me to create a record with `-1` as the ID and `true` as active when only a name is passed. When deserializing from `{\\\"name\\\":\\\"Ada\\\"}`, it yields the canonical constructor result of `(0, \\\"Ada\\\", false)`, which is a nice assertion to have.\\n\\nI’m contemplating whether to add a third test for serialization and deserialization round-trip, but I think it may not be necessary. I need to ensure there's a metadata entry.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_Xrkc06albV6qfG1ZnbIXFCCy|fc_0f177e74ce86ea830169f028cd4434819183ec761ffc000abf", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg -n 'queryAllDeclaredConstructors|queryAllDeclaredFields|allDeclaredConstructors|allDeclaredFields' -S schemas tests/src | head -120"}}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_2ppmtlWUANruEn3FcEM9QScZ|fc_0f177e74ce86ea830169f028cd4448819184d919f9d99e0c2e", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find schemas -name '*reachability*' -o -name '*reflection*' | head -40"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.4", "usage": {"input": 988, "output": 2554, "cacheRead": 65408, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 68950, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777346733492, "responseId": "resp_0f177e74ce86ea830169f028ae15648191bb263a91558fcd74"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_Xrkc06albV6qfG1ZnbIXFCCy|fc_0f177e74ce86ea830169f028cd4434819183ec761ffc000abf", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "rg: schemas: No such file or directory (os error 2)\ntests/src/org.eclipse.jetty/jetty-server/12.1.3/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/test/reflect-config.json:4:    \"allDeclaredConstructors\": true\ntests/src/org.freemarker/freemarker/2.3.31/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/reflect-config.json:4:    \"allDeclaredConstructors\": true,\ntests/src/org.freemarker/freemarker/2.3.31